CARS4U PROJECT¶

Description¶

Context¶

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in this market.¶

In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.¶

As a senior data scientist at Cars4U, you have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing. For example, if the business knows the market price, it will never sell anything below it.¶

Objective¶

To explore and visualize the dataset, build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars, and generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.¶

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used cars sold in different locations. The detailed data dictionary is given below.¶

Data Dictionary¶

S.No.: Serial number¶

Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name¶

Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)¶

Year: Manufacturing year of the car¶

Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in km¶

Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)¶

Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)¶

Owner: Type of ownership¶

Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg¶

Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC¶

Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp¶

Seats: The number of seats in the car¶

New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)¶

Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs¶

# We shall use a defined function ofr this
def str_to_num(col_val):
    if isinstance(col_val, str):
        return float(col_val.split(" ")[0])
    else:
        return np.nan


str_col = ["Mileage", "Engine", "Power"]
for colname in str_col:
    df[colname] = df[colname].apply(str_to_num)

##let's define a functionn for plotting both histogram and boxplot
def hist_boxplt(data, figsize=(15, 7), kde=True, bins=None):

    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(
        data, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.distplot(
        data, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data.mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data.median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Model performance check¶

  • We will be using metric functions defined in sklearn for RMSE, MAE, and $R^2$.

  • We will define functions to calculate adjusted $R^2$ and MAPE.

  • We will create a function that will print out all the above metrics in one go.

In [67]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def cal_adj_r2(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def cal_mape(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_perf_reg(model, predictors, target):

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = cal_adj_r2(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = cal_mape(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Conclusions, Insights and Recommendations¶

  • We have been able to build a predictive model that can be used by Cars4U to predict the price of a Used Car with an $R^2$ of 0.77 on the training set.
  • Cars4U can use this model to predict the used car price within a mean error of 2.88
  • We found that Engine Displacement, Engine Power, some of the Car brands (like Bently,Lamboghini, Mercedez-Benz,and Jaguar),and Transmission_Manual are some of the factors which tend to increase the price of used cars.

  • We found out that Mileage, Kilometers_Driven,Car_Age, all the Owner_Types, and all Seats classifications are some of the factors which tend to decrease the price of used cars negative.

  • Maruti and Hyundai car brands are the most selling used cars. The stock of these two brands should always be available and properly priced.

  • The major markets for used cars are Mumbai, Hyderabad, Coimbatore, Kochi, and Pune with each selling more than 750 cars. However, based on our pricing model, selling more cars in Coimbatore, Bangalore, and Hyderabad will have higher positive impacts on pricing than other locations. It is therefore recommended that more sales effort should be concentrated on those price-increasing locations.

  • Used Cars between 4-8years old sell more than cars of other ages. Each year increase in the car age reduces the price by 6.73 INR. Therefore, stocking of more recent cars generally is highly recommended.

  • Diesel and Petrol cars sell better than other fuel types. However, diesel cars are better priced and their sales should be driven by good business strategies.

  • Manual transmission cars sell over 250% better than automatic transmission cars whereas automatic cars are over 300% better priced. Therefore a good stock mix of the two types of the used cars is recommended.

  • First owner type of used cars sell over 500% more that other owner types and are also better priced. This type of cars should dominate the company's stock.

  • 5-Seater cars sell over 750% more than other types of used cars but the more expensive used cars are the two seaters. However, the 5-seater cars have the highest negative impacts on price among other types based on our model. Therefore, ensuring that every 5-seater car has other price-increasing features aforementioned can potentially assist in having a good price scheme for such car.

  • It is also recommended that used cars with low mileage and kilometers driven but high engine displacement volume and engine power should be stocked more as these features are all car price-increasing.
